onoured by blue plaques","hasStoryPackage":"false","lastModified":"2014-07-30T18:01:13Z","body":"<p>The esteemed intellectuals on the panel responsible for selecting the historical figures to be honoured with English Heritage's famous blue plaques are a discerning crowd. They have previously rejected proposals for plaques outside the former homes of Bob Marley, Elizabeth Taylor and even Thora Hird – a decision<a href=\"http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-17895094\" title=\"\"> that provoked criticism</a>.</p><p>It is perhaps no surprise, then, that English Heritage's decision to appoint a slew of celebrities to join them in their deliberations has caused outrage – and, indeed, resignations.</p><p>The <em>Observer</em> has learned that two members of the panel felt forced to quit three weeks ago. Their resignations were provoked by the appointment of the man who brought <em>Big Brother</em> to the UK and who is now chair of the arts council, Sir Peter Bazalgette; FA chairman Greg Dyke; the broadcaster and art dealer Philip Mould; scientist and TV presenter professor Lord (Robert) Winston; TV host and physicist Professor Brian Cox and banker Rupert Hambro.</p><p>David Edgerton, professor of the history of science and technology at King's College, London, one of the two rebels, along with the prizewinning architectural journalist Gillian Darley, said: \"Instead of a <a href=\"http://www.english-heritage.org.uk/about/who-we-are/how-we-are-run/committees-and-panels/blueplaquespanel/\" title=\"\">blue plaques panel</a>, English Heritage are creating a white-men-off-the-telly panel, with a banker added.</p><p>\"It is hardly expert, especially in history, and is not representative. Such a panel may wish to fund its own plaque scheme, but it should not call itself the blue plaques panel, nor should a scheme advised by such a panel be in receipt of public money. People are not so dumb that they want their blue plaques decided on by people they might have seen on television.\"</p><p>Edgerton, a historian and a panel member for six years, who only learned of the new appointments when he examined the addressees of the agenda to the next meeting, said he feared the appointments had been made purely to encourage donations. He said: \"English Heritage is the custodian of the blue plaques panel, not its owner. Proposers, supporters and the public will rightly expect the blue plaques panel to be expert, particularly in history. They will also expect it to be representative so that plaques are awarded to people distinguished in all fields, including those currently under-represented.\"</p><p>Darley, an architectural correspondent at the <em>Observer</em> in the 1990s and biographer of the social reformer Octavia Hill, said she was appalled by the lack of female names among the appointments. She added that she also felt that the panel's important role was being undermined and that others on it were considering their positions. \"The appointments are all male and, with the exception of Brian Cox, they are all over 60,\" Darley said. \"And the other point is that they are all busy people. I doubt they will find time to scrutinise these decisions.</p><p>\"Bonnie Greer was appointed to the panel last year and they make a lot of that. But, well, let's just say her attendance record hasn't been very good. I've met her. Once.\"</p><p>It has been a troubled few years for English Heritage's blue plaque panel, which was <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/culture/2013/jan/06/blue-plaques-cut-government-funding\" title=\"\">temporarily suspended in 2013</a> while new funding was sought after government cash had been cut.</p><p>Two panel members, Dr Celina Fox and Margaret Pelling, subsequently <a href=\"http://www.telegraph.co.uk/history/10158413/Blue-Plaque-scheme-in-turmoil-as-a-quarter-of-panel-resign.html\" title=\"\">resigned in protest</a> at the need to make efficiency savings to the scheme, including cutting its support staff by 30%.</p><p>Edgerton said he would also have resigned at the time but had been assured that the character of the panel would \"continue to be one in which the people of London could and should have confidence\". But, Edgerton said, it had become clear that this would not be the case. In his resignation letter to the chairman of English Heritage, Sir Laurie Magnus, Edgerton wrote: \"By examining the addressees of the agenda for the next meeting, I discover that you are creating a panel of radically different character, one which I believe is neither appropriately expert or representative.</p><p>\"I am therefore resigning as I do not believe that such a panel, not least without an expert staff, can properly carry out the functions entrusted to it.\"</p><p>Edgerton and Darley were asked whether they wished to assist in the appointment of their replacements, but have declined. In a letter to Professor Ronald Hutton, chairman of the panel, Edgerton said: \"I don't feel able to recommend anyone, nor indeed to recommend that anyone accept an invitation to serve. I am sorry to be blunt, but English Heritage have clearly made up their mind what panel they want, and have got it.\"</p><p>In a response to Edgerton, Magnus said he had \"made a personal commitment to keep the scheme as an important part of our activities\". He added: \"We are most grateful for your contribution and hope that we will demonstrate that we have not lost touch with the key founding principles behind the blue plaques.\"</p><p>A spokesman for English Heritage said further appointments were being made, including that of Professor Martin Daunton, master of Trinity Hall, Cambridge. He added: \"We were disappointed to receive the resignations of two blue plaque panel members.</p><p>\"We are confident that, once complete, the panel will represent the full range of in-depth knowledge and expertise required to consider all the different blue plaque nominations.\"</p>","headline":"Accusation of 'white men off the telly ta