s, but she was never recognised – I think it's a shame and a disgrace. So posthumously this was one thing I thought I could do for her, to campaign for the blue plaque.\"</p><p>The plaque was unveiled by the critic and author Bonnie Greer, who called her \"an inspirational figure, a beautiful gracious goddess, with an impeccable instrument in her voice\".</p><p>The only other black woman honoured with a blue plaque, unveiled five years ago, was the <a href=\"http://www.english-heritage.org.uk/discover/people-and-places/womens-history/women-celebrated-by-blue-plaques/\" title=\"\">19th century nurse Mary Seacole</a>. Greer said that although Welch was never a political campaigner, her quiet determination to pursue her own career was itself an example to others.</p><p>\"She presents another pathway, another option, she shows the way for any young black woman, any woman, any person who wants to go their own way in life.\"</p><p>Bourne, a friend of Welch's until her death in 2003 just short of her 100th birthday, said when she made two films with the singer Paul Robeson, who was a passionate campaigner for black civil rights, he urged her to join the fight. \"She said 'Paul, my father was African and native American, my mother was Scottish and Irish, I've got four people within me, I can't make a stand for all of them, you'll have to excuse me.' He roared with laughter and hugged her, and the subject was never mentioned again.\"</p><p>Welch, who was born in New York in 1904, and first launched the Charleston craze on Broadway – a song she detested for its idiotic lyrics, according to Bourne – also became famous for her performance of Porter's Love For Sale, a song then seen as a scandalous reference to prostitution.</p><p>She partly came to Paris and then London to escape discrimination, became renowned as a cabaret and club singer, and in 1934 became the first black broadcaster to win her own BBC radio series, Soft Lights and Sweet Music.</p><p>Her career was relaunched at the age of 75 when Derek Jarman included her heart-stopping performance of her signature song, Stormy Weather – which she first sang in 1933 – in his 1979 film The Tempest. The scene of her singing with unruffled serenity<a href=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=857Ste6wylM\" title=\"\"> surrounded by a chorus line of half naked sailors</a>, was described by George Melly as \"arguably the campest, most sparkling moment in the history of cinema\".</p><p>She starred aged 81 in a Donmar Warehouse revue, Jerome Kern Goes to Hollywood, which transferred and brought her back to rapturous acclaim on Broadway after half a century.</p><p>After Welch's death Bourne discovered that she had had a long discreet affair in the 1930s with the newspaper heir David Astor. Astor was then unmarried, and Welch's brief marriage to a fellow musician had ended in his death – but the affair never became public and ended when his formidable mother Nancy Astor intervened. On the day Astor married another woman, Bourne discovered, Welch took a rare day's sick leave from the West End show she was appearing in.</p><p>Greer said: \"The last year I lived in New York was 1986, and all the talk then was of two singers – Whitney Houston, and Miss Welch, and they had much in common in representing another tradition in black music, in their approach to their art, in their perfectionism and integrity. There was a danger that Miss Welch, somebody who never banged a drum for themselves, or went for the huge film roles, could have been forgotten in the shadows. That should not be allowed to happen.\"</p>","headline":"Elisabeth Welch honoured with English Heritage blue plaque","trailText":"Singer who had own radio series and was nominated for Olivier and Tony awards is second black woman to be so honoured","shouldHideAdverts":"false","publication":"The Guardian","showInRelatedContent":"true","thumbnail":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2012/3/1/1330626426107/WELCH-003.jpg","wor